VAT administration in the Czech Republic and in the Federal Republic of Germany
Report on the control test
foreword
Taxes are the main source of income for public finances.
One focus of the activities of the SAIs should therefore be to review this area.
This applies in particular to sales tax fraud.
This alone causes tax losses of an estimated € 100 billion annually in the European Union1.
Already at the VI. EUROSAI Congress 2005 in Bonn, participants pointed to the need for increased cooperation.
This makes it possible for the audit offices, for example, to exchange audit approaches and to optimize the audit practice.
Value added tax (VAT) is particularly suitable for cooperation as it is harmonized within the European Union.
In 2006, the courts of auditors of both countries audited for the first time in parallel in the field of VAT.
The corresponding audit report was published in 2008.
Since VAT fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, there is a need for close cooperation between the courts of auditors. This will allow a comprehensive assessment of whether the measures taken are effective in effectively counteracting VAT fraud.
The two SAIs decided to continue their cooperation and conducted a second parallel audit. VAT administration in the Czech Republic and in the Federal Republic of Germany Report on the control audit
1 Introduction
Exam number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892
Subject: (CZ) Administration of VAT (D) Bilateral audit with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter NKÚ), control audit
Audit objective:
(CZ) The VAT administration and the treatment of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as Germany) should be examined. In addition, the procedures used by the tax authorities in intergovernmental mutual assistance should be examined.
(D) The purpose of the audit was to evaluate how the tax administration has implemented the recommendations made by the courts of auditors.
In addition, further test fields - linked to the VAT - should be processed.
The findings made should be compared to determine whether taxation procedures can be optimized.
The examination period was the years 2006 to 2008, including relevant information from the period prior to the examination period until the completion of the examination.
2. Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination
The audit offices of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed to a control audit for the administration of the VAT.
At the previous parallel audit, they had uncovered suspicions of intra-community turnover,
which made a re-examination appropriate.
On the basis of the audit findings, the two SAIs issued recommendations for the administration of the VAT.
The aim of the control review was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented. In addition, the identified suspected cases should be investigated.
The audit also looked at other issues. These included selected cases of high-risk intra-Community sales, mutual assistance in the recovery of VAT receivables and the VAT audit of large companies.
The audit offices established:
1. Recommendations based on the previous review
• Recommendation 1: The rules governing the registration of taxpayers should be harmonized within the EU
At the first audit, the SAIs compared the USt registration procedures in the two states and found differences that caused problems.
The SAIs therefore recommended harmonizing the registration of taxpayers within the EU.
This was also taken up at EU level.
The draft amendment to Council Regulation No 1798/2003 provides for the extension of the existing databases in the EU, including a VAT identification number database.
The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxpayers and their possible deletion.
The SAIs expected Member States to agree on appropriate arrangements in line with their policy decision to remove unreliable entrepreneurs from the VAT system as early as possible.
On the last version of the draft, the Member States reached political agreement in ECOFIN.
These common rules are no longer included. The two courts of audit regret that.
They still consider such regulations important in order to prevent VAT fraud.
• Recommendation 2: Monthly Submission of Summary Reports As a result of the first audit, the SAIs recommended that Member States should submit the Summary Reports (ZMs) on a monthly basis.
The amounts of intra-Community sales could then be checked in a more timely manner.
Council Directive 2008/117 / EC amending Directive 2006/112 / EC on the common system of value added tax, designed to combat intra-Community trade tax fraud, has reduced the deadline for submission of the CM to one month.
In the CZ, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the VAT Act that came into force on January 1, 2010.
In Germany, implementation only came into force on 1 July 2010. Thus, it has not transposed the duty to pay ZM on a monthly basis into national law.
• Recommendation 3: Data reconciliation of USt pre-registrations and the ZM in Germany for more reliable VIES data and proposal to review the merger of the procedures for USt pre-registrations and ZM The German tax authorities have taken up the recommendation issued by the Bundesrechnungshof and set up a working group, the to develop possible solutions.
The work is not finished yet.
The Federal Court of Auditors will observe the further development.
• Recommendation 4: Exchange on successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level During the first audit, the two audit offices agreed that an effective risk management system can not be developed by one Member State alone.
Successful criteria as well as elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.
Failing that, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.
The SAIs found that the two Member States use different risk management systems that have both strengths and weaknesses.
The NKU examined the system of information exchange within the EU - EUROCANET, while the Federal Court of Audit focused on German participation in the "Risk Management Platform".
2. Control audit of selected intra-Community transactions
The audit offices had jointly investigated revenues at the first audit that were in doubt as to whether they had actually been executed or had been declared differently by the taxpayers of the two states in the VAT returns (or UST declarations) or by ZM.
The audit offices selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between the Czech Republic and Germany for the control audit.
The examinations by the tax offices (FÄ) of both states were not completed at the conclusion of the first parallel examination.
The audit showed that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed. The respective tax administrations had taken appropriate measures to this effect (including subsequent VAT determinations or the prevention of input tax refunds).
3. Review of selected, particularly risky intra-Community transactions
Also included in the audit were highly risky intra-Community transactions between EU taxpayers included in the EUROCANET system.
EUROCANET is used to identify high-risk taxpayers.
Member States may participate in this system on a voluntary basis.
The CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET. Germany has a passive status, ie it does not participate in data exchange within the framework of EUROCANET.
From the point of view of an active participating State, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.
As a result, no information could be obtained on which suppliers with German VAT IDs would have been classified as high-risk cases.
The NKU found in the selected transactions both normal business transactions and those suspected of VAT fraud, including carousel fraud.
The FÄ's were only able to check limited transactions with high risk. This was particularly the case with so-called "missing traders", whereby examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to prove fraud to the taxpayer.
In case of suspected carousel fraud on imports and exports
It is recommended that customs and tax authorities cooperate more closely in order to be able to track the identity of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final customer.
Germany and a number of other countries have refused to actively participate in EUROCANET, as they believe that there is insufficient legal basis.
The Federal Court of Auditors found that the German tax authorities use other instruments to detect risky taxpayers.
Nevertheless, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.
The Council of the EU agreed on a draft regulation,
created by the EUROFISC.
The experience accumulated so far with EUROCANET should be incorporated into the planned network for the fight against VAT fraud.
4.Continuous mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.
Therefore, requests for inter-state assistance in the recovery of claims in CZ and Germany are handled in the same way.
The Federal Court of Audit and the NCP have compared the statistics that both Member States have sent to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.
These statistics contained discrepancies.
The two courts of auditors consider a renewed discussion on statistics at EU level to be useful in order to avoid any remaining discrepancies in the future.
If this does not happen, the statistics can not be used appropriately for comparisons.
In addition, the statistics should include more information about the VAT.
An analysis of detailed data may help the Commission to assist Member States in their efforts to combat VAT fraud.
Both SAIs consider that Member States with a low recovery rate should strive to at least reach the average recovery rate.
The Commission should assist Member States, if so desired.
5. VAT inspection at large companies
The SAIs analyzed the legal situation regarding the USt audit of large companies in both countries.
In addition, they used a questionnaire to collect information from the tax authorities, which they considered important in this context.
It became clear that the situation in both countries is different.
For the selection of risky cases, CZ has a system that includes a large amount of relevant data (including information on VAT audits, balance sheet data and profit and loss accounts).
Overall, the VAT control can be effectively controlled and analyzed.
In 2012, a special tax office for large businesses is to be established.
In Germany there is no comparable system. This complicates the control and analysis of the VAT control overall.
The German tax authorities concentrate more on the selection of relevant individual cases and rely in particular on data from the USt pre-registrations or VAT declarations and the ZM.
Various risk management components, which are to be improved, support the evaluation of this data.
