4. Examination of the administration of turnover tax in selected areas
4.1 Implementation of recommendations from the first joint audit
4.1.1 Implementation of recommendations in the Czech Republic
Recommendation 1
Harmonization of conditions for the registration of taxable persons within the EU Supported
Following the results of the first audit, the Czech Court of Auditors recommended that the VAT registration requirements should be adjusted and new rules should be introduced for the cancellation of registration in the Czech Republic.
These amended rules should more effectively reduce the risk of potential tax evasion.
In certain cases, it was found that the FÄ did not cancel the VAT registration of taxpayers who did not fulfill their obligations under Czech Law No 235/2004 (hereinafter referred to as the "VAT Act").
So far, the Czech Ministry of Finance has submitted no amendment to oblige the FÄ to extinguish, if the taxpayers repeatedly submit no VAT declarations.
According to the Czech VAT Act, the FA may ex officio delete the registration of a taxpayer if: (a) the taxpayer has not made any sales for twelve consecutive months and has not informed the FA of the reasons therefor; b) the taxpayer has failed to fulfill its obligations under the USt Law; c) the taxpayer no longer fulfills the requirements for tax liability.
The first examination revealed that due to the existing legal situation, FA Prague 1 must delete the VAT registration "foreign taxpayer" 3 with effect from 31 January of the following calendar year if they were not required to declare and pay USt in the current calendar year ,
The FA Prague 1 often did not clear the VAT registration of these taxpayers because the relevant provision of the deadline could not be properly implemented in practice.
The problem was resolved by the amendment to the USt Law, which came into force on 1 January 2009.
Accordingly, the FA has the power to cancel the registration of a foreign taxpayer if, in the previous calendar year, he did not provide taxable or exempt goods or services that are entitled to deduct.
Recommendation 2
Monthly delivery of the ZM
As a result of the first audit, the SAIs recommended that ZM's monthly fee be introduced.
The Council Directive, which reduced the period for the surrender of CM to one month, was implemented in the CZ by the UST Law, which entered into force on 1 January 2010.
The ZM must now be submitted electronically.
In addition, if services whose place of performance is to be determined in accordance with Section 9 (1) of the Value Added Tax Act have to be provided for a person registered as being subject to VAT in another Member State.
The condition is that the recipient is obliged to declare and pay the VAT for these services. This obligation follows from Council Directive 2008/8 / EC amending Directive 2006/112 / EC as regards the place of supply of services.
Recommendation 3
Reconciliation of USt Pre-Declarations Data and ZM to Increase the Reliability of MIAS Data This Recommendation related to German Financial Services.
In its ATIS4 system, the Czech tax authorities automatically reconcile the data on intra-Community sales from the VAT returns and the ZM.
Recommendation 4
Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level
The proper collection of VAT is an indispensable prerequisite for the proper functioning of the EU single market.
Therefore, the fight against VAT fraud is of primary interest and has received considerable attention in recent years.
The significance of this is demonstrated, inter alia, by an investigation published by the European Commission in October 2009.
In it, an external expert estimated the VAT shortfall for the 25 Member States over the period 2000-2006. After evaluating the available data, the tax loss for the period mentioned was estimated at between € 90 and 113 billion. This was based on the EU-25 losing an average of 12% of their turnover tax every year.
The estimated tax loss for CZ in 2006 was 18%.
The first audit found that one Member State alone can not develop an effective risk management system (RMS).
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS need to be shared and implemented in each Member State.
With regard to the RMS, the Czech Court of Auditors has examined the system for the exchange of information within the EU (EUROCANET).
For this, risky intra-Community transactions carried out by taxpayers within the EU and recorded in EUROCANET were selected (see section 4.3).
The purpose of the EUROFISC network is to optimize mutual assistance in tax matters and combat VAT fraud more effectively. Cooperation between competent authorities should be improved in order to detect fraud as early as possible.
Later, EUROFISC could be used as a tool to estimate the risk potential of intra-community transactions.
The ECOFIN Council6 approved EUROFISC on 7 October 2008, and at the same time adopted the principles for the operation of the system.
The model for EUROFISC is provided by EUROCANET, developed by the Belgian tax authorities in cooperation with the other Member States and supported by the European Commission and OLAF7.
The purpose of the system is to detect risky revenues and to identify entrepreneurs involved in organized VAT scams.
