4.2 Control audit of selected intra-Community transactions
The first audit examined joint transactions that had doubts as to whether they were actually carried out or that discrepancies had been found in the notifications of taxpayers in both Member States.
The two SAIs selected nine cases of intra-Community supplies of goods between the Czech Republic and Germany for which the tax audit by the FIs of the Member State concerned had not yet been completed at the time of the previous joint investigation.
1)
In the first quarter of 2005, a Czech taxpayer purchased goods worth EUR 22 686 from a German taxpayer.
The Czech taxpayer did not declare the acquisition in his VAT declaration that the German taxpayer did not have a VAT identification number in the period mentioned, but only a tax number for intra-German sales.
Through international administrative assistance under Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the competent Czech FA had received information that according to the German VAT law, the supplier of intra-Community goods does not need a VAT identification number in order to benefit from the exemption of intra-Community goods.
The Czech Court of Auditors' inspection showed that, according to the Czech FA's examination, the Czech taxpayer filed an additional VAT declaration, declaring the purchase of goods at the above-mentioned value, while asserting his right to deduct input tax in the same amount ,
2)
A Czech taxpayer is said to have acquired goods worth EUR 12 561 from a German taxpayer in the fourth quarter of 2004.
However, he stated that he did not purchase the goods and therefore did not declare it in his VAT declaration.
On the basis of a provision of Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003, the German tax authorities refused to handle the request because the turnover linked to the acquisition did not exceed the threshold of EUR 15 000.
Since the Czech FA could not obtain documents, the tax audit remained fruitless and the original tax assessment persisted.
The Czech Republic Court of Auditors' verification showed that the Czech FA received two spontaneous information from Germany in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003, according to which the German taxpayer invoiced the goods in question to a Slovak addressee.
The Czech taxpayer purchased the goods from the Slovak taxpayer and indicated the purchase in his October VAT return statement.
