• The FAC did not find any suspicion of risky transactions when examining the early warning information.
The taxpayers concerned were constantly monitored because their data was stored in EUROCANET.
• FÄA's verifications of risky transactions failed to demonstrate, on the basis of the accounting records submitted, breaches of the rules on the calculation of the taxable amount and VAT, although they identified inconsistencies in the transport and storage of the goods or revealed business relations with shell companies from other Member States.
• Reviewing individual business transactions was complicated because certain taxpayers could not collaborate with the FÄ and could not be contacted.
The competent FTEs reviewed most of the high-risk taxpayers and transactions mentioned in EUROCANET's early warning messages.
Their ability to review risky revenues, especially so-called "missing traders" are limited.
In particular, a mere examination of the documents can hardly prove the fraudulent activity of the taxpayer.
Stricter taxpayer registration requirements for VAT purposes and greater flexibility in canceling registrations would be helpful in combating VAT fraud.
Taxable persons involved in fraudulent carousel transactions may be registered for VAT purposes to simulate fictitious deliveries of goods throughout the EU or to provide formally correct tax documents to other taxpayers, who then claim unauthorized tax deduction.
In the case of suspected carousel fraud related to imports and exports, it is recommended that customs and tax authorities cooperate more closely to track the identity of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final customer.
Member States may participate on a voluntary basis in EUROCANET.
The fact that three large Member States (Germany, Italy and the United Kingdom) did not participate was seen by the European Parliament at the end of 200811 as a weakness of the system, which should be remedied by establishing a mandatory EUROFISC network.
4.3.2 Findings in Germany
The Federal Court of Audit evaluated data available at the Federal Central Tax Office, including those from EUROCANET.
They served as the basis for the selection of six German taxpayers whose files were reviewed.
Both Germany and a number of other countries refused to actively participate in EUROCANET.
