4.4 Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
4.4.1 Inter-state assistance in the recovery of claims in the Czech Republic
Legislation on intergovernmental mutual assistance for the recovery of specific claims in the EU is essentially based on
Council Directive 76/308 / EEC on mutual assistance for the recovery of claims relating to measures forming part of the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund, and of levies and customs duties;
Council Directive 2001/44 / EC amending Council Directive 76/308 / EEC on mutual assistance for the recovery of claims relating to measures forming part of the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund, and levies and customs duties and VAT and excise duties and taxes
Commission Directive 2002/94 / EC laying down detailed rules for the application of certain Articles of Directive 76/308 / EEC on mutual assistance for the recovery of claims relating to certain levies, duties, taxes and other measures.
The CZ implemented Council Directive 76/308 / EEC by Law No 252/2000 on intergovernmental mutual assistance for the recovery of specific assets.
After the adoption of Council Directive 2001/44 / EC, it also had to be transposed into Czech law. At the same time, an amendment to the aforementioned law was required.
In this context, legislative amendment No 191/2004 on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of specific claims has been adopted.
A new relevant piece of legislation was adopted by Commission Regulation (EC) No 1179/2008 of 28 November 2008.
The annexes to this regulation contain new application forms to be used from 1 January 2009. Furthermore, the regulation makes the electronic transmission compulsory and obliges the requesting authority to certify the conformity of all sent documents with the respective original.
Essential principles of international mutual assistance for the recovery of claims are:
1. The principle of reciprocity applies;
2. Assistance shall always be provided only on application and in fulfillment of all conditions;
3. Assistance shall not extend to claims which are considered a criminal sanction in the requested State;
4. The procedure of intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of claims shall be conducted in accordance with the national law of the requested State;
5. In the recovery procedure, foreign claims do not take precedence over domestic claims;
6. Assistance shall be provided only for the recovery of undisputed claims;
7. The principle of exhaustion applies: the requesting State must use all the means to which it is entitled under national law to recover the claim.
Law No 191/2004 provides for three forms of administrative assistance: the provision of information, the service of legal acts and the actual recovery.
Procedure for outgoing requests to other EU Member States
The competent authority must send the request for information, the request for legal acts or the request for recovery, together with the relevant documents, to the Ministry of Finance of the Czech Republic electronically via the respective Financial Directorate.
The Ministry of Finance of CZ arranges the translation of the request into the language concerned, scans it with all the attachments and sends it via the communication network or common interface CCN / CSI to the competent tax authority of the respective state.
A request for recovery assistance must meet the following requirement: the claim must exceed € 1,500 and may not be more than five years old.
The requested authority may refuse recovery if the requirements are not met.
Procedures for incoming requests from other Member States
The receipt of requests from other Member States must be confirmed by the Ministry of Finance of CZ as soon as possible, at the latest within seven days.
If it disagrees with the request, it must inform the requesting authority of the reasons for the refusal, giving the specific provisions of the Directive on which it is based.
The relevant notification must be sent no later than three months after the date of receipt of the request.
Upon receipt of the request, the Ministry of Finance will verify that the request meets all legal requirements.
Thereafter, it should send the request to the competent FA through the relevant Financial Directorate. If the request for recovery is granted, the FA shall, inter alia, determine the financial circumstances of the debtor, eg. B. Excerpts from the land register, inquiring about existing bank accounts and registration of motor vehicles at the Admissions Office.
After six months from the date of receipt of the acknowledgment of receipt of the request, the Ministry of Finance of the CZ shall inform the applicant authority of the result of the inquiries made.
The requesting authority must also be informed if the taxpayers concerned are unreachable and the claim can not therefore be recovered.
All successfully collected sums must be transferred to the requesting authority within one month of collection.
The Czech FA dealing with the recovery may, with the consent of the requesting State, agree on the demand or installment payment.
The interest or penalty payments imposed on the debtor for the period of delay in accordance with Law No 337/1992 on the administration of taxes and charges
stand by the requesting State.
In particular, in the years 2006 and 2007, the Ministry of Finance of the Czech Republic forwarded to the competent FA the received recovery requests with a delay.
The same applied to the forwarding of requests for recovery from the Czech FTA to the competent authority in the requested State.
The audit found that the Ministry of Finance has violated the Law on Inter-State Mutual Assistance for the Recovery of Debts. It had failed to inform the competent authority of the requesting Member State of the state of the recovery procedure within six months of confirmation of receipt of the request.
The situation has improved since 2008.
Statistical data
In accordance with § 13 (4) of Law 191/2004, the Ministry of Finance of the Czech Republic prepares statistics for the European Commission by 15 March each year. This contains the number of requests sent and received in the previous year as well as requests for information, service of legal acts and recovery, including the amount of the respective claims.
Based on data provided by the Member States, the European Commission is preparing its report to the Council and the European Parliament on the application of the provisions on mutual assistance for the recovery of claims.
