4.4.2 Inter-state assistance in the recovery of claims in Germany
Legal basis for intergovernmental assistance in tax matters are the Community legislation Council Directive 2008/55 / EC of 26 May 2008 (EC Recovery Directive) 14 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1178/2008 of 28 November 2008 (EC -Durchführungsrichtlinie).
For better readability and clarity, the EC Recovery Directive codified Council Directive 76/308 / EEC of 15 March 197616, the provisions of which had been substantially amended several times.
It regulates, among other things, the recovery of VAT and taxes on income and assets including the associated interest, fees and late payments.
The EC Recovery Directive was transposed into German law by the Recovery Act (EC) 17 of 3 May 2003.
The enforcement procedure in Germany is regulated in the Tax Code (AO).
Section 117 (2) of the AO provides that the tax authorities may provide inter-state legal and administrative assistance by virtue of international treaties and by applicable law of the European Communities and by virtue of the EC Administrative Assistance Act.
Part Six of the AO (Sections 249-346) contains the legal provisions governing the enforcement proceedings.
In particular, the administrative acts of the tax authorities regulate the enforcement and enforcement instructions.
The Federal Ministry of Finance agreed with the representatives of the highest tax authorities in the Länder on the principles of administrative assistance in tax matters and transferred its own competence in this area to the Federal Central Tax Office18.
General conditions for the admissibility of a request for assistance are:
• The legal requirements must be fulfilled (§§ 251, 254 AO).
• All funds available domestically have been exhausted.
• The demands for which assistance is sought are non-appealable.
• The period between the issue of the writ of execution or the date on which the claim or title became unassailable and the date of the request may not exceed five years.
• The claim must be at least 1 500 euros.
Procedure for outgoing requests to other EU Member States The German requests for the recovery of tax arrears are processed by the FÄ enforcement authorities through the competent central authority and the Federal Central Tax Office of the relevant foreign authority, eg. For example, the Czech CLO.
The details are set out in the memorandum on intergovernmental assistance in tax collection (recovery) of 19 January 200419.
This leaflet is currently being revised by a federal / state working group and adapted to the new recovery directive.
The request, together with attachments, will be forwarded electronically by the FA to the Central Authority.
The latter checks whether it is correct in terms of content and form.
If not, the request will be returned to the relevant FA.
Otherwise, it will be forwarded to the Federal Central Tax Office.
The Federal Central Tax Office then takes over the necessary communication with the relevant foreign authority.
Procedures for incoming requests from other EU Member States
Requests for recovery from other Member States are recorded in the Federal Central Tax Office, which sends an acknowledgment of receipt within ten days.
It also checks if the formal requirements are met.
In principle, the Federal Central Tax Office forwards these requests to the Central Authority, which forwards them to the relevant FA and supervises the execution.
The Federal Central Tax Office also sends interim and final reports.
If the processing of a request takes longer than six months, it reminds the Central Authority of the obligation to submit an interim report in accordance with Article 16 of Commission Directive 2002/94 / EC.
After examining the formal and substantive conditions for the admissibility of the request, the executing agencies shall announce appropriate measures.
All sums recovered must be transferred to the bank account specified in the request within one month of receipt.
