4.4.4 Comparison and evaluation
In the case of recovery, the provisions of EU law apply to all EU Member States for intergovernmental assistance.
The procedures for handling requests are therefore similar in the CZ and Germany.
The Federal Court of Justice and NKÚ have compared the statistics sent by the two Member States to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.
There were inconsistencies.
In its 2006 report2020, the European Commission recommended that Member States make their statistics with greater care.
In 200921, the Commission concluded that, despite a larger number of requests for assistance, the discrepancies in statistics have diminished.
Both SAIs consider a renewed discussion at EU level on statistics to be useful in avoiding the remaining inconsistencies in the future.
If this does not happen, the statistics are conditionally meaningful and can not be used for comparisons.
Moreover, the SAIs believe that the statistics should show both the annual number of requests and the nature of the claims (eg VAT, income tax) and the amounts recovered per Member State.
By further analyzing the statistics provided by Member States, the Commission could assist Member States in assessing their anti-VAT fraud policies.
As the recovery rate per Member State can be calculated, the SAIs support the idea that low quota Member States should at least strive for the average recovery rate within the EU.
At the request of a Member State, the Commission could play an active role.
The foreign claims for recovery received at the Ministry of Finance CZ were delayed, especially in the years 2006 and 2007, to the responsible FÄs.
The same applies to the requests for recovery made by the Czech FZ.
The audit revealed that the Czech Ministry of Finance was in breach of Law No 191/2004 on intergovernmental recovery aid in that it did not notify the competent authority of the requesting Member State within six months from the acknowledgment of receipt of the request for recovery.
4.5 VAT inspection at large companies
4.5.1 Sales tax audit of large companies in the Czech Republic
General
The taxation procedure for large companies is subject to the same rules as other taxable persons.
The audit of large enterprises is regulated by the Czech Law No. 337/1992, the "Tax and Charges Administration Act".
The Czech Ministry of Finance defines large enterprises as natural persons who have set up a business or legal persons established for the purpose of conducting business operations and whose net turnover for the tax period concerned is at least CZK 2 billion according to the income tax or corporation tax return.
The taxpayer is classified as a large enterprise on the basis of the amount of turnover according to income or corporate income tax return in the respective tax period; first time for the year 2003.
A natural or legal person is no longer classified as a large business for purposes of turnover taxation if its net turnover in the taxable period is less than CZK 2 billion for three consecutive tax periods. The period begins at the end of the taxation period for which the conditions were met for the first time according to the tax return.
A taxpayer can only be removed from the list of large enterprises if at least one tax type has been previously audited for a tax period.
By the end of 2009, all large farms were audited at least every five years.
Since 2010, taxpayers are to be assessed in writing at least every two years. The subsequent control measures are designed to eliminate the tax risks and their negative effects on the proper taxation and collection.
The examinations by the FÄ should focus on at least one type of tax; they usually include several tax periods.
The taxable large companies were audited by the special audit offices or audit services of the competent FÄ, which were set up at a total of 13 FÄ.
A special audit unit carried out audits in its local area of responsibility in accordance with the instructions of the Head of the Financial Directorate.
At the same time, she also tested
Taxable persons with unusual and special business activity and
those whose examination required a high degree of expertise and time.
Also taxpayers with complex site distribution and organizational structure are audited,
Taxpayers who are suspected of large-scale tax evasion
and taxpayers who belong to chains and networks that are suspected of being heavily tax evaders and unjustified deduction of input tax.
Information on the number of examinations carried out by the special auditors of the FÄ and the additional taxable results of these examinations are shown in Table No. 3.
The Czech Ministry of Finance has submitted a proposal for the amendment of Law No. 531/1990 for the regional tax authorities. In particular, it proposes the establishment of a special tax office with national jurisdiction for selected taxable persons (legal entities set up for the purpose of economic activity with a turnover of at least CZK 2 billion).
