General
The VAT audit of large companies is not particularly regulated in Germany. Audits are subject to the general provisions of the • Tax Code (AO), • the Financial Administration Act (FVG) and • the Auditing Regulations (BpO).
There are also work aids.
fiscal code
The provisions of §§ 193 to 203 AO "Section 4 External Audit" contain in particular rules on the admissibility of an external audit and their material scope, distribution of responsibilities, form and content of the audit announcement, audit principles, duties of the taxpayer to cooperate and requirements for final discussions and for the transmission of the audit report.
External examinations are carried out by the competent FÄ (§ 195 AO).
According to § 5 (1) No. 1 in conjunction with § 19, the Federal Central Tax Office is responsible for external audits of the FÄ.
The nature and extent of this cooperation will be agreed between the authorities involved.
In addition, the Federal Central Tax Office may require that certain establishments designated by it be audited at a certain point in time.
In that case, it may lay down rules on the external audit of those taxable persons.
Internal Audit Regulations In accordance with Article 108 (7) of the Basic Law, the Internal Audit Regulations (BpO 2000) were adopted with the approval of the Bundesrat.
It applies to external audits of the state tax authorities and the Federal Central Tax Office.
According to § 3 BpO companies are regularly classified in size classes.
Large farms are subject to a follow-up inspection (Item 4.2 BpO).
According to section 33.1 BpO, each responsible tax authority has to keep a list of companies within the meaning of the regulation.
Administrative tools
